    <p>
      Mata has happy memories of facing Arsenal during his time with Chelsea. The Spain midfielder scored four goals in five appearances versus Arsene Wenger's team, claiming three wins against a solitary loss.

      He featured when the sides last played each other, sharing a goalless draw at Emirates Stadium in February and believes a more entertaining match is likely between two teams free to show their attacking prowess.
    </p>
    <p>
      "The Emirates is a great stadium and I hope we have a nice game and bring back three points to keep moving up the table."
    </p>
    <p>
      Mata made his case for a return to the United starting line-up by coming off the bench to score the only goal in their triumph over Crystal Palace at Old Trafford on 8 November. The break for international fixtures followed and the 26-year-old believes a little downtime is important as the English season closes in on one of its most gruelling periods.

      "We've just had a few days off that helps you to switch off both physically and mentally with a view to Christmas â€“ the busiest period of the season when we play many games in a short time," he said.
    </p>
